# Install the required packages
First, install the packages, and when asked for the Kerberos and Admin server names enter the name of the Primary KDC:

Configure replica KDCsâ€‹
Note: When installing a replica KDC, the hostname and admin server name should match those of the master KDC.â€‹
Database propagation copies the contents of the primary database but does not propagate configuration files, â€‹
stash files, or the kadm5 ACL file. The following files must be copied by hand to each replica                       â€‹
krb5.confâ€‹
kdc.confâ€‹
kadm5.aclâ€‹
master key stash fileâ€‹

Once you have installed the packages, create the host principals for both KDCs. â€‹

$ kadmin -q "addprinc -randkey host/kdc1.example.com"â€‹
$ kadmin -q "addprinc -randkey host/kdc2.example.com"â€‹
â€‹
Extract the key file for the kdc2 principal, from the replica server (kdc): â€‹
$ sudo kadmin -p ubuntu/admin -q "ktadd host/kdc2.example.com"â€‹

Next, there needs to be a kpropd.acl file on each KDC that lists all KDCs for the realm. For example, on both the primary and secondary KDC, create /etc/krb5kdc/kpropd.acl:â€‹

$ host/kdc1.example.com@EXAMPLE.COMâ€‹
$ host/kdc2.example.com@EXAMPLE.COMâ€‹

â€‹Create an empty database on the secondary KDC: â€‹
$ sudo kdb5_util create -sâ€‹

Now install kpropd daemon, which listens for connections from the kprop utility from the primary KDC:â€‹
$ sudo apt install krb5-kpropdâ€‹

From a terminal on the primary KDC, create a dump file of the principal database: â€‹
$ sudo kdb5_util dump /var/lib/krb5kdc/dumpâ€‹

Still on the Primary KDC, extract its key: sudo kadmin.local -q "ktadd host/kdc1.example.com"â€‹
On the primary KDC, run the kprop utility to push the database dump made before to the secondary KDC:â€‹

$ sudo kprop -r EXAMPLE.COM -f /var/lib/krb5kdc/dump kdc2.example.comâ€‹
Database propagation to kdc02.example.com: SUCCEEDED

ğŸ” Verifying KDC Propagation & Setting Up Replication
After pushing the Kerberos database to the secondary KDC, look for a **SUCCEEDED** message â€” this confirms the propagation was successful.

â— If you see an error instead, check the log file on the secondary KDC:
/var/log/syslog

Automate Database Propagation with Cron
To keep the secondary KDC updated, set up a cron job to syn the database regularly.
The following example pushes the database every hour:
# m  h  dom mon dow   command
0 * * * * root /usr/sbin/kdb5_util dump /var/lib/krb5kdc/dump && /usr/sbin/kprop -r EXAMPLE.COM -f /var/lib/krb5kdc/dump kdc2.example.com

â–¶ï¸ Start the Secondary KDC
Once replication is set up, start the KDC daemon on the secondary server:

$ sudo systemctl start krb5-kdc.service

ğŸ§ª Test the Secondary KDC
To verify it's working:
Stop the krb5-kdc service on the primary KDC:
$ sudo systemctl stop krb5-kdc.service

On a client machine, try requesting a Kerberos ticket:
kinit username@EXAMPLE.COM

